            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "> Neovim's built-in formatter feature (`gw` and `gq` maps) incorrectly indent's markdown list items when some line starts with one of keyword like `if`, `for`, `while` (maybe more others). This happens only with enabled option 'smartindent'.\n\nFrom `:help 'smartindent'`:\n\n```vimdoc\n\t\t\t     *'smartindent'* *'si'* *'nosmartindent'* *'nosi'*\n'smartindent' 'si'\tboolean\t(default off)\n\t\t\tlocal to buffer\n\tDo smart autoindenting when starting a new line.  Works for C-like\n\tprograms, but can also be used for other languages.\n```\n`'smartindent'` is for C-like languages. If you turn it on in Markdown files, Neovim will dutifully attempt to indent them like C files. This isn't a bug, it's a usage error.\n\nIf I were to propose a change here, it would be to add a big fat warning to the top of the documentation, because the name of this option is catnip for anyone with indentation problems. Nothing about this option is \"smart\".\n\n> I notice that `vim` has no indentation definition for markdown...\n> I'm wondering if something similar to https://github.com/corriander/vim-markdown-indent, integrated to `vim` itself could be the right solution to this problem?\n\nI don't think indenting is the right tool for the job here (I would probably look into `'formatexpr'` if anything), and I would be highly wary of taking inspiration from a small stub that was abandoned 11 years ago. This was just someone attempting to scratch an itch and almost immediately giving up. That said, I would not fully dismiss the idea of a better-than-nothing indentation plugin for Markdown.",
